Installing Eggdrop (devinkbrown fork)

This is the quick install guide; if you have had little or no experience
with UNIX or Eggdrop, READ THE README FILE NOW! This file is best for
experienced users.

NOTE: This fork uses Meson + Ninja. The traditional autoconf/make build
system used by upstream Eggdrop is not present here.

DEPENDENCIES

  Required on all platforms:
    - Tcl development headers  (tcl-dev / tcl-devel, version >= 8.6)
    - Meson  >= 0.57.0
    - Ninja  (any recent version)

  Optional:
    - OpenSSL development headers (libssl-dev)  -- TLS support
    - Python >= 3.8 development headers          -- Python scripting module
    - zlib development headers (zlib-dev)        -- compress module
    - liburing                                   -- io_uring backend (Linux)

  Debian/Ubuntu:

      sudo apt-get install meson ninja-build tcl-dev libssl-dev

  Fedora/RHEL:

      sudo dnf install meson ninja-build tcl-devel openssl-devel

  macOS (Homebrew):

      brew install meson ninja tcl-tk openssl@3

  Windows (MSYS2/MinGW-w64):

      pacman -S mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-meson mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-ninja \
                mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-tcl mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-openssl

    Winsock2 and MsWSock are provided by the Windows SDK and are linked
    automatically -- no extra package is needed for the IOCP backend.

  Windows (MSVC — Visual Studio 2019 or later):

    1. Install Visual Studio with the "Desktop development with C++" workload,
       or install the standalone Build Tools:
           https://visualstudio.microsoft.com/downloads/#build-tools-for-visual-studio-2022

    2. Install Meson and Ninja.  The easiest way is via pip in a normal
       Command Prompt (not a developer prompt):

           pip install meson ninja

       Alternatively, download the Meson MSI installer from
           https://github.com/mesonbuild/meson/releases

    3. Install dependencies using vcpkg (recommended):

           git clone https://github.com/microsoft/vcpkg
           cd vcpkg
           bootstrap-vcpkg.bat
           vcpkg install tcl:x64-windows openssl:x64-windows

       Then set the toolchain so Meson finds the packages:

           set VCPKG_ROOT=C:\path\to\vcpkg

    4. Open an "x64 Native Tools Command Prompt for VS 2022" (or 2019).
       This sets up the MSVC environment (cl.exe, link.exe, etc.).

    5. Configure and build from that prompt:

           meson setup build/ --vsenv ^
               -Dtcl_root=%VCPKG_ROOT%\installed\x64-windows ^
               -Dopenssl_root=%VCPKG_ROOT%\installed\x64-windows
           ninja -j%NUMBER_OF_PROCESSORS% -C build/

       Meson detects cl.exe automatically when run from a developer prompt.

    Winsock2 (ws2_32.lib) and MsWSock (mswsock.lib) ship with the Windows
    SDK included in every Visual Studio installation and are linked
    automatically by the build system.

  Cygwin:

    Cygwin compiles on the POSIX path using select() as its I/O backend.
    Install the following packages via the Cygwin setup tool:

        Interpreters: tcl, tcl-devel
        Net:          openssl, libssl-devel
        Devel:        meson, gcc-core, git, ninja

QUICK STARTUP

1.  Configure the build directory:

        meson setup build/

    Common configuration options:

        meson setup build/ -Dipv6=true -Dtls=enabled -Dpython=auto

    To list all available options:

        meson configure

2.  Compile using all available CPU cores:

    Linux / Cygwin:

        ninja -j$(nproc) -C build/

    macOS:

        ninja -j$(sysctl -n hw.logicalcpu) -C build/

    Windows (MSYS2 shell or MSVC developer prompt):

        ninja -j%NUMBER_OF_PROCESSORS% -C build/

3.  Install (default prefix is /usr/local; override with --prefix at setup):

        meson setup build/ --prefix=$HOME/eggdrop
        ninja -C build/ install

    Or install to a custom path after the fact:

        meson install -C build/ --destdir /path/to/install

4.  Since version 1.8, Eggdrop can use SSL to protect botnet links. If you
    intend on protecting botnet traffic between Eggdrops, you must generate
    SSL certificates. See doc/TLS for details.

[The following steps are performed in the directory you installed Eggdrop into]

5.  Edit your config file completely.

6.  Start the bot with the "-m" option to create a user file:

        ./eggdrop -m LamestBot.conf

7.  When starting the bot in the future, drop the "-m". If you have edited
    your config file correctly, you can type:

        chmod u+x LamestBot.conf

    From then on, you can use your config file as a shell script:

        ./LamestBot.conf

    The top line of your script MUST contain the correct path to the Eggdrop
    executable.

8.  It's advisable to run your bot via crontab or systemd so it restarts
    automatically if the machine goes down. Eggdrop includes a helper script:

    For a systemd job:

        ./scripts/autobotchk [yourconfig.conf] -systemd

    For a crontab job:

        ./scripts/autobotchk [yourconfig.conf]

9.  Smile. You have an Eggdrop!

I/O BACKENDS

  The build system automatically selects the best available I/O backend:

    Platform           Backend     Notes
    ------------------ ----------- ------------------------------------
    Linux >= 5.1       io_uring    Requires liburing; kernel polling
    Linux              epoll       High-performance, persistent interest
    macOS / BSD        kqueue      High-performance, persistent interest
    Windows (native)   IOCP        Zero-byte overlapped WSARecv/WSASend
    Cygwin / fallback  select()    Portable; rebuilds fd_set each loop

  To force select() (e.g. for debugging), build without the relevant
  library: configure without liburing and on a system without epoll/kqueue.

DEBUG BUILDS

  To build with debug symbols and extra logging:

      meson setup build/ -Degg-debug=true
      ninja -C build/

MODULES

  Modules are compiled automatically by Meson. Each module can be
  individually enabled or disabled at configure time:

      meson setup build/ -Dmodule-compress=false -Dmodule-python=false

  To see all module toggle options:

      meson configure build/

This is the end. If you read to this point, hopefully you have also read
the README file. If not, then READ IT!

Have fun with Eggdrop!

